        <Document ID="FD4FF368-A7F5-41E5-8EB0-58FB689EA3D3">
            <Title>Waterfall</Title>
            <Text>In software, it is never true that one can get it right the first time around.  

If you think that you know what you are doing, then you are employing a technique called the Waterall method.  

Even really smart people don't get it right most of the time - for example, refer to most existing multi-tasking libraries and the agony that these have caused.

[If you thought that you got it right the "first time", odds are that you have done this before.] </Text>
            <Comments>Currently, multi-tasking is considered "hard",  Most of the problem is due to Accidental Complexity - the use of Time-Sharing (a hard problem) and the idea that memory needs to be shared.  Both of these are based on old-fashioned criteria that have little to do with generalized multi-tasking.</Comments>
